Triumph of the populist right in Austria, together they make up 29%
The early elections to the Austrian parliament have brought, according to the first approximate results, an appreciable weakening of both parties of the current grand coalition and an expressive strengthening of the party of the populist right.
Strong and special losses have suffered the Austrian People&#39;s Party (OVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously shaking.
On the contrary, the leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZO), the head of the government of the state of Carinthia, Jörg Haider, prepares his triumphant return to national politics.
According to approximate results, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of votes, thus losing 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last elections of 2006. .
Worse still has ended the OVP that loses 25.6 percent, almost nine percent of votes.
They are the worst results, literally catastrophic, in the history of these two great Austrian parties since the postwar period and especially for the popular ones who called these early elections.
Still in early July, when the OVP left the coalition, the popular had a considerable advantage in terms of preference over the SPO.
It is clear, however, that the voters punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculation was heard about the resignation of the party president and, until today, vice chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be achieved this Monday at the exceptional meeting of the party&#39;s presidency.
Such evolution would evidently facilitate the path of the constant and more approximate starting point of the electoral results, that is, of the renewal of the great coalition between SPO and OVP.
Considering that the reinforcement of both parties of the populist right - the Liberals (FPO) have won about 18 percent and the BZO, eleven percent of the votes - and that the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fears that The same thing happened in 1999 when the popular negotiated with the populists (then the FPO was a unit, but in 2005 it dismembered from BZO) for a coalition government that came to generate a sanction from the European Union.
Haider clearly bets on this evolution, who has already announced that he is prepared to collaborate with any party and that he is already assuming his return to Vienna, to national politics.
The Green Party has also managed to reach parliament although it has lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party clearly exceeded the four percent limit and therefore is not part of parliament.
Fight at gunpoint: the MP3 Player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every cell phone plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
What seems clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Yet there are enough reasons for the man to buy only the player.
The choice depends practically on the way of its use and on the requirements of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for you to acquire the most modern turntable to hear the latest Maxim Turbulenc album on it.
On the other hand, this type of musical products such as LP records no longer come out, and in terms of their quality there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues music are crowding on your shelves, you are probably dreaming, at least, of this type of turntable.
This is the same with music on the way, that is, compressed, simplified music - MP3 music.
And here there are categories of price and quality.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, the same as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly try twenty crowns flea market helmets.
Two ends, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
You also decide the battery life
Some of the best players do much more than just play music and even what most phones do not.
No current device is as universal as the telephone.
Faced with the most basic functions such as telephoning, sending messages, you can play music and video, record both, you have a better or worse camera and you can even navigate.
And when we take into consideration the Smartphone and PDAs, they will also have a small computer in their pocket.
This is a small miracle since no refrigerator knows how to grill and no television can photograph.
The universality of mobile phones also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on the mobile, the sooner the screen indicator will light up asking to be recharged.
And music playback is one of the biggest energy suckers.
Few are the mobiles that can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest ones) clearly have a higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap mobiles will not play for more than two hours.
If in addition to this, on top of that, they call constantly, get each other, for more safety, a charger for work - this also applies to the most expensive devices.
With the MP3 player this problem is not going to be, because even the worst can endure at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem happens when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, only part of the devices have the universal USB connector and, furthermore, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, it is possible to record music directly on the memory card, but only in some non-shrink reader units can the small memory cards used in mobile phones be connected.
In the players, with some exceptions (iPod), no special software is necessary.
It is enough to fill the device with music through the USB of the computer.
Most mobiles and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the artist, album title, genre or also according to the user&#39;s evaluation.
Some devices only show a directory with a tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
When choosing a specific device, be interested in the resistance of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to music in the background and you are going to listen to it every day for only a little while, like on the tram, then any mobile that you play is enough for you.
What practically any mobile truly achieves.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile phone or the player plays the music.
The MP3 is reproduced by all and, practically, almost all the music that reaches you will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it, the absolute majority of devices play music in WMA format.
The minuses include the AAC format (format used by the Apple company and its iPod).
The best mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough through the mobile internet to visit the relevant pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album.
This service alone could be a strong argument for acquiring a mobile for music.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is miserable and the majority is limited only to the subjects of fleeting success of the radios.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry a cell phone.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you will find your mobile in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry a headset or at least a handsfree with you.
If not, you can use a built-in player that almost every mobile has, even if it is at least an MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many mobile phones with music will be their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already buy a good Walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the absence of a classic headphone jack.
The best, even when it comes to the technical side, such as phones equipped with a 3.5mm input. for classic headphones, they cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing more than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are actually handled by anyone.
The minimal functions, its handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the turntables is evident.
It does not represent a threat in the sense that by mistake we connect to the internet with our mobile phone and, consequently, a gigantic account for data download.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (for example, the Vodafone 527) generally have a slot to change the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card it will reach two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are normally equipped with only a 2 GB maximum capacity card.
Only the most expensive ones have a memory of 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB), you do not need to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you consider yourself among the most demanding music lovers, take advantage of the most specialized walkman-mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have independent keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of the same player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman line phones have almost the same use as a standalone MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, about four thousand crowns, but with a greater memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and accumulator (normally 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the brand cited above brings you MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will already arrive this year in the Czech Republic.
Probably
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer practically all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we are still missing something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It probably won&#39;t be long in coming.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written in mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunication Office (ČTÚ), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulating roaming charges, a paradoxical situation is likely to be reached - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them. from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, since we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to lament that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, also said that there is no longer a place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find a frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator in the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in prices to which the classic operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile to the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is a place for these types of operators and that they can be successful.
For the rest, you don&#39;t have to look too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the premiere of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 clients and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U: fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
Furthermore, in order for them to function effectively, they have far fewer clients than a traditional operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, are often counteracted by the offer of more adjusted services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap as the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a non-trivial target group can also be a good blow.
This operator specifically targets man.
&quot;The right man chooses Mobilking - he is the operator you like and who you can trust,&quot; says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say if a similar concept like that of Poland could hook in our country.
Vodafone spokesperson Miroslav Čepický doubts this: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated &quot;
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech R. it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region, &quot;Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone conversation for mobil.cz.
Indirectly he assured that the current mobile phone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather the opposite, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition for Telefónica O2 in the field of business customers.
&quot;We have a great interest in this, to be able to offer our clients not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony.
And the sooner the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly come across all Czech mobile phone operators.
With some of them we have managed to advance the meetings, &quot;said the group&#39;s spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe better times flash.
It seems that, due to unofficial information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
&quot;At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
Until now no one has approached us with a complex and serious project in this field &quot;, Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesperson for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, exceptionally in accordance with O2&#39;s opinion, adds: &quot;Until today we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop.&quot;
And he adds: &quot;In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this time we should already have on the table a specific contract that could be studied in such a short horizon &quot;
Vodafone directs its attention rather to the fulfillment of the own requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: &quot;We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider it precisely the greatest contribution from the customer&#39;s point of view.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for fast mobile internet. &quot;
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to lower prices and thus lower profits.
So why facilitate entry to the competition?
When operators want to achieve something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U: fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U: fon by the T-Mobile partnership.
This is attested by the public information accessible on the ČTÚ web pages.
But right now U: fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: &quot;Furthermore, it was not long ago that the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was opened up to a fourth operator.
With regard to the nature of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean great requirements for him and, above all, for his services. &quot;
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the complete disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just about the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately does not have any jurisdiction to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (ÚOHS).
However, she expressed her typical position on this problem.
&quot;The entry of a virtual operator to the mobile telephony market would be possible after the conclusion of an agreement on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile telephony operator and a virtual operator.
Until today no agreement has been closed since the offer of the potential interested parties was not interesting enough for the classic operators &quot;, added to our question Kristián Chalupa, from the Department of Foreign Relations of the ÚOHS.
These formulated statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that must represent the interests of consumers this is more than a consideration, apart from that they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad, where virtual operators operate normally, we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the drop in prices of mobile telephony services&quot;
Obviously, the pressure regarding the correct functioning of the market means and the lowering of prices are not within the interest of the ÚOHS.
What is really dramatically shocking in this whole case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a fluke presents itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a tough fight for competition.
&quot;The Office in this regard has not found signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding increase in responsibility in their actions in the market.
Rather, the necessary tools to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators are lacking, as well as telecommunications regulators, &quot;added Chalupa to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many sticking points.
Obviously there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market naturally none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge, an agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has a monopoly on its network.
Therefore, in a specific segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should represent a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly in a similar way.
The current complaints from the interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators they run into many similar impediments.
Placing responsibility on the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the telecommunications field of which the ÚOHS washes its hands on all this matter.
We have already met him in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was presented a short time ago to extend the competence of ČTÚ in the field of commercial tenders, which was not carried out, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known to the representatives of ÚOHS, but it is clear that their interests lie elsewhere.
Everything is fine, when no one is looking
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator continues to operate unnoticed, since there are already quite a few in the Czech mobile phone networks.
They are companies that set their own prices for mobile phone services, which, however, only part of them are public.
Usually these are companies that are dedicated to multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife, and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a select few get the price list from these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same, ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile phone operators prohibit this type of resale.
&quot;If cases such as the ones you cite were discovered, one could speak of an infringement of the contract conditions that could lead to the end of collaboration with the given society,&quot; Martina Kemrová answered the question about this problem.
But it is highly unlikely that an activity of this kind carried out by mobile phone operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of clients.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they obtain a not inconsiderable profit and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of possible problems: &quot;the law allows speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of clients.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card of their phone is not in their name, so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators. &quot;
This is precisely what should seem minimally strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, a new question appears for the ÚOHS.
If mobile phone operators squint at this type of procedure, why are they blocking the virtual operator&#39;s entry?
It is necessary to add that ÚOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want to, it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not. allow.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As it was already clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator in the mobile telephony market brought a significant decrease in the prices of services.
At the same time, in practically all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators more or less tried to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were practically all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of the service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, at this time the regulatory bodies have intervened and in none of the cases did they defend the operators but rather their clients.
Either with formal measures or informal pressure, they managed to create the first virtual operator and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body passes this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot help but be impressed that the confusion of the attributions in these cases suits them.
But let&#39;s not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will probably start to move again.
If any of the operators allows a virtual mobile phone operator to enter, it will be difficult for ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we will perhaps stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four performances of the new version of the Czech official anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the day of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new hymn was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theater under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one with a male voice and one with a female voice, another with Chorus and another instrumental.
The singing is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the hymn arrangements are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this national Czech chant one of the most beautiful hymns.
The Czech Radio already said before that it intentionally chose for the Solo singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
&quot;From the beginning I have tried with both of them and later, also, with the Choir to pay attention to the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it had consonance,&quot; he commented.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home was first played in 1834 on the stage of the State Theater in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it their own.
The first verse of the song after the rise of Czechoslovakia in 1918 naturally became a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the rise of the independent Czech Republic.
How the &quot;new&quot; hymn sounds
The Prague MHD brings us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the date on which the first passengers enter the subway, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a ticket is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company. of paper.
This can be purchased at the moment by almost one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (it will be valid as of January 1, 2009) and simultaneously load it onto their chip card at the infocentres and transport company posts at the stations of the Metro, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The vouchers can already be purchased from yesterday on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about the ticket booths in subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue to get a normal ticket.
The voucher is purchased online, and the Opencard is recharged at one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
&quot;In these places there is a window available to passengers with trained personnel who help those interested with the purchase online and also with the recharge of the voucher purchased on their card,&quot; said the spokesperson for the project, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic voucher in the Opencard in the automatic vending machines that are in some lobbies of the metro.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket machine, and travelers have probably already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, IP Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
&quot;Now there are five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty,&quot; Opatrný added.
The voucher is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid voucher will be charged only to it.
The electronic vouchers from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is, on the ring-road trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 that are mainly used by the inhabitants of the towns of central Bohemia.
&quot;In the trains assigned to the integrated transport of Prague there are inspectors equipped with a reader card that will help to confirm the validity of the time and the zone of the voucher&quot;, as explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that establishes the schedules of the public transport of Prague.
Bypass buses have their reader cards mounted in the driver&#39;s locker.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany him with the Opencard in the place designated for it on the side of the Cashier.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the voucher.
&quot;If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the vouchers, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information,&quot; Drápal completed.
Passengers who do not travel on the bypass buses and do not remember when the validity of the voucher expires can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the screen of the machine, you will be shown the information about the validity of your document.
The Southeast wanted to be part of the US in a referendum
Sudeten Germans asked in 1945 that Fumaba be part of the United States.
This is what is extracted from the letter that is kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
With this wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans presumably approached the US president in 1945.
It results from the letters that are kept in a private archive and that today are kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
The Germans of Český Krumlov request in a letter to the American president not to allow the return of the &quot;Šumava land&quot; - occupied by Hitler on the basis of the Munich Pact - back to Czechoslovakia.
&quot;We have understood the situation correctly and we really want your word that the American units are arriving in German lands not as oppressors or enemies but as liberators&quot; is written in the letter, signed with &quot;the people who carry the destiny of Šumava in your heart&quot;.
In view of the fact that the union of Czechoslovakia with the Southeast Germans presumably supposes - according to them the Czech national character - a hope only in brutality, inconsideration, misunderstanding, pressure and slavery, the authors beg in the letter to the American president to assume for today and forever to Šumava under a protectorate.
&quot;We cannot believe that without considering the opinion of four million inhabitants it will hand us over to a foreign state that oppresses and rejects minorities and that in no way collaborates with the victory of the allies,&quot; the letter wrote.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is presumably fear of reprisals from the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot;.
If the president of the USA presumably doubted this idea of the German šumavos, it would suffice to organize a referendum in the šumava lands on whether its inhabitants want to be part of the United States or live under its patronage.
Although the text of the letter, with the current knowledge we have of post-war history, may sound a bit childish to us, according to some specialists it rightly paints the expectations of the Germans of the Southeast of that time.
Although the Czech Germans must have had a slight intuition that their expulsion from the republic was going to be discussed, only a few admitted this possibility.
Some hoped that the United States and Great Britain would negotiate for the Sudetenland some clear form of autonomy.
Others believed that they will stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is even confirmed by the Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice.
He was in the war, as a German from Budějovice, enlisted in the Baltic navy.
When the British captured him at the end of the war and placed him in the Holstein prison camp, dozens of Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
&quot;They believed that when they returned home, the Czech would be good for them,&quot; said Chalupa.
None of the German prisoners who lived before the war in Czechoslovakia, according to him, expected that on the basis of the Benes Decrees they would be removed from the Republic.
