Rats have feelings too
It is said that a rat or a cockroach, sensing the danger, flees, why is it also afraid?
Joseph Le Doux, the scientist in the field of neurology is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can you control if they, behaving in the same way as us, feel the same?
In an internet magazine called &quot;Edge&quot; for many years the contributions of famous scientists have been published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series the answers chosen to the question What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that I or someone else could not prove until now, although we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope for it because all human brains have the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we dedicate ourselves to other species and include the questions about sensation and consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as other animals: it plays dead, runs away, or attacks.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists make conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Naturally I don&#39;t think so.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transmit our subjective experience to that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated by human consciousness of the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (because of their participation in short memory and executive functions that direct behavior).
This broad part is much more developed in the case of people than that of other primates and seems to be absolutely lacking in other creatures.
Taking into account at least the aspects related to our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex, including knowledge about who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is a reason to suppose that even man differs from other primates .
One other peculiarity is found in the linguistic nature of man: Since most of his experience is linked to language, this often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even though consciousness would not depend on language, it would influence it in such a way that the consciousness of animals, however created, would in many cases differ from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is difficult to explain how the consciousness of other animals works.
If that, as something interesting and subjective, cannot be measured because it has the special hardware, nor can it be analyzed through our experiences, then his research presents us with big problems.
Most of my interventions refer to the content of conscious experience, but at the same time there is also another aspect of consciousness that should be easier for scientific investigations.
One could investigate the consciousness processes of animals without taking their contents into account, and that is what happens during short memory studies of primates, especially in the example of visualization.
But with this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, the essential thing passes rather to the neutral correlates of consciousness than to the causal mechanisms: The two may or may not be similar.
Interestingly, this approach highlights the importance of the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex for the formation of visualization.
And what results from that for the sensations?
I owe it to the fact that a part of the brain that is responsible for this is activated in the emotional system, the same thing that happens with fear.
What we describe as fear is therefore a mental state in which we are when the activity of the brain occupies a space in the defense system (or its consequences, such as the reactions of the body).
Seen from this point of view the sensations are very fixed to part of the cerebral cortex which distinguishes primates and especially man.
From the point of view of the linguistic nature, they follow fine classifications of sensations because we can differentiate and classify the states with the help of words and grammar to be able to describe the states of others as well as ourselves.
For example Antonio Damasco, on the contrary, thinks that the sensations are derived from the simple activities of the parts of the cerebral cortex responsible for bodily feelings and the brain stem, the same Jaak Pankseep thinks, but he concentrates more on the trunk brain.
As this network has not changed much during human evolution, it can refer to absolutely different types and their sensations.
For theoretical reasons I cannot go against that, but I consider it unlikely.
Pakseep argues that what rats and men feel as fear, possibly that feels in two cases as well: But how can you control whether rats and men behaving alike feel the same way?
Seeing the danger, a cockroach runs away, why is it afraid?
I am of the opinion that similarity of behavior does not yet prove similarity of experience.
It is true that the neural comparison helps: rats and men have similar brainstem, cockroaches on the other hand do not have at least one brain.
Is it the brain stem that is responsible for sensations?
Even if it is possible to test it for men: How can it be tested in case of rats?
I think rats and other mammals, possibly cockroaches too (who knows?), Have sensations.
But I don&#39;t know how you can prove it.
I prefer to investigate emotional behavior of rats than emotional sensations because their sensations are supposedly fundamentally different from us (because human consciousness refers to special circuits and the tongue).
In any case, progress in the field of neurology is expected here as long as the same is measured in rats and in men.
Since I do not investigate the tongue and consciousness of rats, as well as sensations, I do not know if they exist.
It can be said that I cannot see beyond my nose, but I would rather advance than work permanently without results.
Well, I&#39;m a practical emotionalist.
