Hidden by the sprawling park theme of the great Orlando, a few miles from the bright, noisy and colossal city, is a quiet town, where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are very evident.
Eatonville, the first fully black-inhabited city incorporated in the country and the childhood place of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: &quot;the city of five lakes, three croquettes, 300 men of color, 300 good swimmers, many guavas, two schools and not a jail. &quot;
Now it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Fair in Eatonville to honor Mrs. Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet, in many ways, the city she described - making it a tourist spot as well by including it in the Florida travel guide produced by the Federal Writers&#39; Draft Season&#39;s Project - remains a place apart. .
The city remains independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Ms. Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida are often reluctant to share their true ideas with the white man, who &quot;knows so little about us and who does not know what he is missing. &quot;
Even now, in the year that a black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, has called for attention to begin a dialogue on the issue of race, many remain wary of the outsider.
&quot;We are very cautious about the way our story is told,&quot; said Jones Hortense, 59, a lifelong resident and member of the city&#39;s oldest church.
&quot;It has to be correct.&quot;
Eatonville has always been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is at the same time a historical model of the affirmation of blacks and a community of almost 2,400 people who live under a level of poverty twice the national average.
It is a literary center, but also a repaired example of the rural culture of the Black South - sometimes scorned, sometimes praised - that was born out of slavery in America.
No wonder, if those who reside here are both proud and reserved.
And the concern for Eatonville&#39;s image really started with Zora, as no one here calls her Mrs. Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through her profound dialect books such as &quot;Mules and Men&quot; (1935) and &quot;Their Eyes Were Watching God&quot; (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guide transformed the city, just off Route 17, a highway that runs through central Florida often forgotten in black history and human drama.
Having a concrete face in both life and literature, Ms. Hurston led her readers into the store owned by Eatonville&#39;s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then into more private areas.
&quot;Off the road on the left,&quot; he wrote, &quot;there is the modern brown public school with its white finishes, its well-maintained gardens and playgrounds, cared for by Howard Miller, as he can barely read and write.&quot;
She also mentions Widow Dash&#39;s new husband and writes that Glenn Lee &quot;sells drinks of all kinds and anything goes with temporary rooms.&quot;
Thus, in just a few hundred words, Ms. Hurston relates Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
Obviously this Fodor didn&#39;t.
In fact, not everyone appreciated the portrait.
