&quot;I capture the master offstage to extract his character&quot; Günther Bauer_Photographer
Neither heels nor ruffles nor premiere outfits.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, stripped of the concentration in the interpretation to obtain the relaxed aspect of the man or the woman.
To one side the artist.
To the other, the person.
Inseparable except in privacy, in those moments outside the public, when finding the privacy of a gesture, the depth of a stolen look or the expressiveness of hands, carefree because they are not going to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer alternates in &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; the theatricality of some productions with singers, dancers and guitarists with that lesser-known side of these masters.
With this proposal, the photographer collects the particular iconography of flamenco from different areas.
Included in the program of the Month of Flamenco Photography, the exhibition &quot;reflects the international importance of flamenco, growing every day&quot;, explains the creator, who clarifies that &quot;Flamenco-people&quot; &quot;can be anybody but, when looking at the photos, the observer realizes that these are not the typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed &quot;in the street&quot; are artists capable of transmitting passion, sadness, joy on stage ... captivating the public.
You don&#39;t have to take photos of the stage to capture the personality of these artists.
They carry their personality and character within.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco &quot;.
With the flavor of the &quot;Cante de las Minas&quot; festival, Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to portray singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
They are portraits that, due to the selection of the camera and the material, are reminiscent of classic photography.
The application of different stylistic means breaks with the classical base of the image, giving it modernity, an idea that reflects how Bauer himself understands flamenco: &quot;A music with very traditional roots, which evolves and surprises every day&quot;.
It is not the action of the dance, the cante or the toque itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, that captivates the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential, with the duende that becomes visible in a way of feeling, of being and of being are and have been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the El Fotomata gallery.
Well-known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, make up this selection of almost seventy photographed artists.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits exhibited in the exhibition.
Bauer&#39;s passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with &quot;Portraits of Veteran Athletes&quot; (&quot;SportARTproject&quot;).
Although the concepts are different in &quot;Flamenco-people&quot;, the photographer admits that &quot;I love portraying people, meeting them and being able to enter their life for a moment, be it a long or a short moment.
