Evolution versus revolution.
This is the second generation Honda Jazz.
Although aesthetically the new Jazz presents a line very similar to the model that happens, the changes introduced in this minivan are numerous.
Among others, it is worth noting an innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new mechanics.
However, before analyzing the new model, it should be noted that this new Jazz arrives six years after introducing the first generation to the market.
Therefore, a first observation is that Honda has renewed this model in a shorter period of time than that used by other manufacturers.
Although in Europe, the Jazz is less known, in other markets this model is a sales phenomenon.
This is the case in Japan, a country where the Jazz has been the most marketed car in 2002 and also in 2008.
Precisely in Japan about a million units of the Jazz have been sold since its launch.
The second market has been that of the Old Continent, with around half a million units in six years.
However, Honda wants this new Jazz to increase sales within the segment.
Thus, while in 2007 the Japanese firm sold a total of 83,000 Jazz units, in 2009 estimates point to 100,000 cars, which would mean a growth of 17% in the European market.
Regarding the Spanish market, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 Jazz units since 2002, which represents 6.7% of Honda&#39;s total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation, those responsible for the Spanish subsidiary expect to sell 2,000 units of the Jazz in a full year.
Precisely the arrival of the new Jazz will allow Honda to greatly alleviate the decline in sales in Spain.
In fact, those responsible for the brand expect to end the year with a total of 22,000 units sold, which is 4,000 less than in 2007, a decrease of 16%.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda has increased its market share in Spain, reaching 1.8%, compared to 1.6% last year.
Likewise, the Japanese firm expects to achieve 2% in 2010.
To achieve this quota, Honda relies on the arrival of another new model.
