The &#39;bee car&#39; that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, specifically, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this little robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Managing Director of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C comes as an extension of Nissan&#39;s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to reinforce the collision avoidance capabilities of the brand&#39;s vehicles.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that closely resembles the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important thing is the bee&#39;s compound eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles that are up to two meters away within a 180 degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to said object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor that immediately results in the prevention of the collision.
&quot;The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a right angle or greater to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that the avoidance maneuver is totally instinctive.
If not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles, &quot;explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and principal engineer for this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot drift up or down, or diagonally; It can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allow it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, for the little robot to avoid collisions.
&quot;This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can run continuously with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we are not talking about gigabytes of memory, not even megabytes. &quot;
This is the first step in developing new instant collision avoidance technologies, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced in series cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium-ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
