According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists reported more than once for drunk driving take the car again.
The alcolock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in exhaled air and prevents starting the car if the driver does not blow open; or when an alcohol concentration is detected that is higher than the allowed one.
Its cost is greater than 1,000 euros and would be borne by the sanctioned person.
In this sense, a study carried out in the US in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with these devices reduce violations by up to 65% during the first year of implementation.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address these behaviors before they lead to criminal offenses.
And facilitate its implementation, since the legal reform can be done by ordinary means, and, nevertheless, the necessary reform by criminal means requires a reform in an organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although it has already been experimentally implemented in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow an initiative of the PSOE in which it is proposed to install this system on school buses, just as it has been carried out in France.
