Talking asleep
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very savvy telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens, you may get scared, but it doesn&#39;t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disturbance called somniloquies.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Surely more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in a lifetime for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nocturnal enuresis (peeing while sleeping) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be the case.
As we have already mentioned previously, they can also be associated with very high fever, situations of stress or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also highly variable.
It may be that he speaks in a calm tone of voice, single words, a murmur or the opposite (screaming, crying, long speeches ...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense, it would be advisable to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives it a way out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a condition of stress).
What can be done is to take into account a series of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid television programs or series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and have a hard time relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will help the child to have a calmer sleep.
Once the somniloquies appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless for the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what happened.
Helpful tips
Don&#39;t wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Although he is talking, he is sleeping and therefore he is resting.
Remember that if he is very distressed during several episodes, it would be advisable to consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common), do not be tempted to question him for information.
You will not achieve anything, because when you are asleep you are not conscious enough to organize your thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, with which you are very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions that you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even as a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, do not worry, it is not bad, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
