In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that make it possible to detect the presence of the virus directly in the blood of donors and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests were based. tests used so far.
Nucleid acid tests made it possible to shorten the period between the moment in which the person has been infected and the moment in which the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
Thus, we substantially reduce the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
