What would be the best method to develop collision avoidance technologies, if not by mimicking nature&#39;s existing obstacle sensors?
For example that of the bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the bumblebees provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-mimicking BR23C robotic car steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions. .
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, director of technology for PR and research and development, at the exhibition.
An important role is played by the compound eyes of bumblebees, which are capable of seeing in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of compound eyes, the engineers used the laser length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle&#39;s microprocessor which immediately transforms into a collision avoidance maneuver.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle, imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
&quot;If this were not the case, the vehicle robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles&quot; - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
You must react immediately and instinctively, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a bumblebee does to avoid other bumblebees.
This process should be done in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, the movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to avoid other bumblebees, here they only used rotary movement and acceleration as a possibility for the car robot, as well as braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means that they have a longer life than lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the capacity of data processing, much less the storage capacity.
This device in each second only has to process some input signals and react according to the case.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with instinctive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, thus using only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
Gigabyte or megabyte memory is not required.
This is the first step in developing the technology to avoid obstacles immediately, which according to Nissan estimates, within ten years will be able to be incorporated into series-produced models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding existing obstacles on his way.
