In the United States, life and health insurance companies, when viewing drug purchase data, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy specialists fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
&quot;There are programs for the protection of personal data, which to the use of the data of the prescriptions in all cases is linked to the approval of the given person.
It must be in independent hands, because if not, &quot;we entrust the chicken coop to the fox&quot; - the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, designer of the program to monitor prescriptions.
Insurance companies make the price of the insurance and the amount of compensation dependent on the client&#39;s state of health and if they believe that the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before they sent the client to a medical check-up and signed the contract with him, knowing the result of the check.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer&#39;s identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the diseases and state of health of the patient. client.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that the level of fat in your blood is practically incurably high, thus you are immediately placed in a higher risk category.
Numerous versions of the program circulate, some even establish a risk number, so that the insurance company in addition to the administration hardly has anything to do, although there are small difficulties in this regard.
Among the disadvantages of the program is, for example, that some medications are multipurpose, for example certain substances are used both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the former are not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process these data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, request the approval of the patient.
