Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historic theaters
Historic cinemas close favoring Multiplexes.
&quot;A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.&quot;
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, a photographer, effectively shows what is happening in large Italian urban centers and also in provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticones in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono theaters in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime .
Almost always they are historical places, full of memory, to disappear, &quot;it is as if a friend died, an acquaintance with whom one shared a piece of place and so much emotion&quot;, observes the director of the new Paradiso cinema, the film that twenty years ago cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize at Cannes won back, which told the poetry of a provincial movie theater and the nostalgia for the way of living the cinema that maybe lost forever.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and paying most of it are mainly theaters of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for its disappearance is the settlement of the multiplex, these three Italian regions are their own, which have registered the largest number of new meticones cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardia in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
&quot;The Italian exercise has developed irrationally&quot; observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, &quot;it would be useful if new structures were built but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all its patrons are willing to be transferred to the meticones.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of the merchants: the previous debt of the state is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view, that the government does not respect the laws that exist.
To sustain the sector, it would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year ”.
The case of Bologna is interesting, the first Italian city to be concerned about closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect single theater cinema in the historic center than on the periphery.
Among the norms provided there are fiscal facilitation measures in favor of the managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the limited traffic zone and will have special rates for parking.
&quot;It is an initiative that I like,&quot; observes Giuseppe Tornatore &quot;and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna, putting other measures in place.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of the meticones, the traditional rooms have to improve the quality of the sound and the image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is an issue that was always important to me: the closure of the Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the &quot;New Paradiso Cinema&quot;, which I had already thought about for a long time. 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the closed Rialto or Quirinale de via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, so as not to see the posters blackened by dust, I turn to the other side ».
