When the energy is born from the waves, the greats take the stage
It is an exterminated deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet&#39;s surface and is being discovered now by the great world energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the greats like Chevron look.
The possibility of collecting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 70s together with the first oil crisis, investigations were intensified.
When the price of oil fell in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was put aside, but now that the environmental issues and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated for 2007 that 15 percent of the world&#39;s electricity need could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of ocean waves.
This amount would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Giants on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build an implant in the North of Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy there are always more and among these companies those who have always voted for traditional energy.
&quot;Chevron is studying the technology on ocean energy - has declared the spokesman of a company associated with the US oil giant to the economic newspaper Wall Street Journal - and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us&quot;.
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the US energy commission, to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is quite an important sign, considering that the US continues to extract oil in Alaska and recently President Bush has activated a plan to drill further.
In addition to Chevron, there is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy that comes from the sea, the total invested so far, although they are not detailed, indicate a growing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts speak of a technology still at the beginning, because there is no doubt that marine energy has a great environmental impact.
For now, impacts such as those Portuguese or Scottish are small and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a large scale, a technology with a higher environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas joined together.
The force of the waves, which makes the boas move up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure turns a turbine which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity is sent to shore through undersea cables.
For now, there are four implants of this type in development, waiting only for federal approval, apart from energy, it could be used for a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces energy for a shopping center and for a parking lot, using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of the water when there are tides, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating movement that powers the generator.
Verdant has said it has a long list of clients waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say in the Institute for the development of electrical energy, merits at this time the potential of the tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tides are more preventable than the wind, the sun or the waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is mainly on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others that approach the coasts, have invested 7 and a half million dollars in 2008 and an investment of 35 million is planned for the 2009.